<s-function-doc>
<s-topics>
<s-topic> dbConnect </s-topic>
</s-topics>
<s-title>
Create a connection to a RDBMS
</s-title>
<s-description>
Connect to a RDBMS going through the appropriate authorization
procedure
</s-description>
<s-usage>
<s-old-style-usage>
dbConnect(dbMgr, ...)
</s-old-style-usage>
</s-usage>
<s-args-required>
<s-arg name= dbMgr >
</s-arg>
a <s-class>dbManager</s-class> object that identifies
the RDBMS (e.g., <s-function name="MySQL.sgm">MySQL</s-function>,
<s-function name = "Oracle.sgm">Oracle</s-function>).
</s-args-required>
<s-args-optional>
<s-arg name= ... >
authorization arguments needed by the RDBMS instance;
these typically include <code>user</code>, <code>password</code>,
<code>dbname</code>, <code>host</code>, etc.
For details, see the appropriate <s-class>dbManager</s-class>.
</s-arg>
</s-args-optional>
<s-value>
an object that extends in a database-specific manner
the classes <s-class>dbConnection</s-class> and 
<s-class>dbObjectId</s-class>.
For instance, the RS-MySQL interface creates connection
object of class <s-class>MySQLConnection</s-class>, 
Oracle of class <s-class>OraConnection</s-class>, and so forth.
<p>
This object is used to direct SQL commands to the database engine.
</s-value>
<s-side-effects>
A connection between the R/S and the database server is 
established, and
the R/S program becomes a client of the database engine.
Typically the connection is through the TCP/IP protocol,
but this will depend on vendor-specific details.
</s-side-effects>
<s-details>
Some implementations (e.g., RS-MySQL) may allow you to have 
multiple connections open, so you may invoke this function repeatedly
assigning its output to different objects.
</s-details>
<s-section name = "NOTE">
Make sure you close the connection using <s-expression>close(con)</s-expression> 
when it is no longer needed.
<s-section name = "REFERENCES">
See the <url url="http://www.omegahat.org" name = "The Omega Project
for Statistical Computing"> for details on the R/S database interface.
</s-section>
